A member of the Intelligence Response Team of the Inspector General of Police (IGP), Inspector Idowu Haruna yesterday told a Lagos State  Special Offences Court that the confessional statements of the alleged kidnap kingpin, Chukwudumeme Onwuamadike a.k.a. Evans was made voluntarily. Inspector Haruna, who was testifying in a trial ordered by the trial judge, Justice Oluwatoyin Taiwo to decide whether the extrajudicial statement made by Evans to the police was voluntarily made, insisted that it was made under a conducive atmosphere. Led in evidence by the prosecution, Adebayo Haroun, at a resumed hearing of the matter, Haruna maintained that Evans voluntarily gave his  confessional at the State Command of the Special Anti-Robbery Squad,  SARS. He denied the claims of Evans that his statement was obtained under duress, arguing that the statements were read to him after documentation and his superior officer also counter-signed the statements after Evans affirmed the contents. Evans was arraigned before Justice Taiwo with three other defendants Joseph Emeka, Chiemeka Arinze, and Udeme Upong over an alleged attempt to kidnap the Chairman of the Young Shall Grow Motors, Mr. Vincent Obianodo. They are facing a seven-count charge bordering on murder, attempt to commit murder, attempt to kidnap, sale and transfer of firearms.